<p><b>Egalitarianism</b> (derived from the <a href="/wiki/French_language" title="French language">French</a> word <b>Ã©gal</b>, meaning <i>equal</i>) or <b>Equalism</b> is a political doctrine that holds that all people should be treated as equals and have the same <a href="/wiki/Political_freedom" title="Political freedom">political</a>, <a href="/wiki/Economic_freedom" title="Economic freedom">economic</a>, <a href="/wiki/Social_justice" title="Social justice">social</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Civil_rights" title="Civil rights" class="mw-redirect">civil rights</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Generally it applies to being held equal under the law and society at large. In actual practice, one may be considered an egalitarian in most areas listed below, even if not subscribing to equality in every possible area of individual difference.</p>
